<br>
My company originally hired me a year ago for &quot;clerical work.&quot; I assumed this meant I was going to be doing reception or some such thing. Also before I signed papers, they told me the salary was going to be mid to high 20's a year. However, when I came in to sign my hiring contract, they brought me in at only 20k a year, and decided that no, I wasn't doing &quot;clerical duties&quot;, but I was doing sales and order entry. Within 2 weeks, that switched to, &quot;No, you're going to be covering for the pregnant lady when she's gone on leave for 3 months. You'll be doing full logistics which covers our world-wide shipping and the international orders.&quot;<br>
<br>
That's typically a job that requires a degree and 5 years worth of experience. I had neither. However, I stuck through and did it anyway.<br>
<br>
Right around that same time they also dropped me from salary to hourly. I didn't really complain because this way, I'm getting paid more. No biggie. It didn't upset me until they said, &quot;Because you are hourly, you no longer get the bonus week at Christmas off.&quot; I pretty much replied, &quot;Bullshit, I have it signed in my contract here by both me and HR that says, &quot;Which in your case is fully paid.&quot; There is no way I'm dropping that.&quot; They sighed and nodded in agreement, and I heard nothing more about it until this morning.<br>
<br>
It took them nearly a year, but they finally did adjust my income to accomodate the cost of living (I'm finally at 27k which is somewhat livable here in Northern California. I have no excessive spending habits, and yet, I'm still barely able to save anything).<br>
<br>
