<br>
The Christmas break is mandatory time off.  Everyone will be gone, so there is no option to work anyway even if you want to.  Salary will be unpaid during this period.  If you have enough accrued vacation time to fill in for the 60+ hours that would constitute the unpaid time off, then you will be paid.  If you have part of this vacation time, you will be paid for those hours.  In this case, Chris has about 26 hours of vacation, so she's going to be out around 40 hours of pay.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now she's got this employment agreement which she signed when she started, and the HR lady signed it to.  It didn't say jack about her pay, which wound up screwing her over for a while, but it did say "in your case, this time off is paid" when referring to the Christmas break.  So they are basically going against an agreement which they are well aware of.<br>
<br>
I actually did a quick search on fixed layoffs (any layoff with a set return to work date) and vacation time.  It's funny that the California Labor Law doesn't come out and say they can't do this, but evidently it does keep them from screwing around with her accrued time and forcing her to use it.  The alternative to being forced to use the time off is to not be paid at all.  The signed document maybe enough to keep them from giving her that time off unpaid.<br>
<br>
According to this article (http://www.metroactive.com/papers/metro/12.20.01/vacation-0151.html):<br>
[quote]<br>
"A forfeiture of accrued vacation is 100 percent illegal," says Miles Locker, the attorney for the state Labor Commissioner. "You cannot take away vacation time that's already accrued. It absolutely violates the California Labor Code." <br>
<br>
Pursuant to the case Boothby v. Atlas Mechanical Inc., it was decided that using and losing vacation time was against state law. In addition, California courts have ruled that vacation pay falls within the definition of wages and therefore cannot be forfeited. Employers have the right to cap accrued vacation, but they should also give employees "a reasonable amount of time to take" that vacation, Locker says. But it seems very few companies are obeying or bothering to familiarize themselves with the law. <br>
